4. Use Hierarchical Clustering and Kmeans to cluster the wines. To do the analysis, make sure first find the best number of clusters. Also, make sure to try multiple linkage options. Then you can pick a preferred solution by studying the clusters patterns to make judgments.

KMN: Best # of clusters

#the computer kept crashing so I reduced the max to 8 from 15
nbc<-NbClust(wine, min.nc=2, max.nc=8, method="kmeans")

## *** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
##                 In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
##                 significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
##                 index second differences plot. 
## 

## *** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
##                 In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex
##                 second differences plot) that corresponds to a significant increase of the value of
##                 the measure. 
##  
## ******************************************************************* 
## * Among all indices:                                                
## * 10 proposed 2 as the best number of clusters 
## * 4 proposed 3 as the best number of clusters 
## * 5 proposed 4 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 5 as the best number of clusters 
## * 2 proposed 6 as the best number of clusters 
## * 2 proposed 8 as the best number of clusters 
## 
##                    ***** Conclusion *****                            
##  
## * According to the majority rule, the best number of clusters is  2 
##  
##  
## *******************************************************************
nbc

## 2  0.4376804
cluster_viz <- function(cluster_stat, features) {
  
  row.names(cluster_stat) = cluster_stat$Group.1
  cluster_stat <- cluster_stat[,-1]
  par(mar=c(8,4,4,2))
  plot(c(0), xaxt="n", xlab="", ylab="", type="l",
       ylim=c(min(cluster_stat), max(cluster_stat)),
       xlim=c(0,ncol(features)))
  axis(1, at=c(1:ncol(features)), labels=names(features), las=2, cex.axis=0.75)
  nbr_clusters = nrow(cluster_stat)
  for(i in 1:nbr_clusters) {
    lines(as.matrix(cluster_stat)[i,], 
          lty=i, lwd=2, 
          col=ifelse(i %in% c(1, 3, 5), "black", "dark grey") )
  }
  text(x=0.25, y=cluster_stat[,1], labels=paste("Cluster", c(1:nbr_clusters)))
}
cluster_viz(wine_hc_mean, wine)

When settling on what would be the best way to convey the many relationships between both clusters, I saw this method posted on the discussion and enjoyed how effective it was at getting the point across, so I applied it to my own code

7. Use daisy() function to calculate the distance and use pam() function to do the cluster analysis. You can also use Silhouette approach to determine the best number of clusters.

disMat = daisy(wine, metric="gower")

sil_width <- c(NA)
for(i in 2:10){  
  pam_fit <- pam(disMat, diss = TRUE, k = i)  
  sil_width[i] <- pam_fit$silinfo$avg.width  
}

plot(1:10, sil_width,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width)
